narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I think this gave me a lot of great insight into the concepts of multivariable calculus. I got much better at visualizing functions in 3D and got a good conceptual understanding of multi, which I think I lacked previously even though I had learned how to apply most of the theorems.
I learned about vectors, line integrals, surface integrals (and their applications)

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I enjoyed the material, and there were several resources made available to make the material more comfortable for us if we were struggling. That said, the pacing seemed far too fast, and it was difficult to remember prior concepts because I didn't fully understand them before we progressed.

strengths: resources offered to the students such as peer tutoring and office hours
weaknesses: in my past 2 math classes, I have had teachers that dont speak great english so they were hard to understand and they didnt explain the concept that well.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Most likely not. It is a useful class for some occupations, but those who would benefit from it later already have it as a requirement for their major, and those who don't need not subject themselves to the horrors of three-dimensional math.
Yes, if they are interested at all in taking higher math courses, physics, chemistry, or engineering. I thought this was a very good course.
No. Unless it is required, it is an unnecessary stress that students shouldnt put themselves through.
